The Inscribed Angle Theorem states that the measure of an angle inscribed in a circle is equal to half the measure of its intercepted arc. This can be proven using the properties of central and inscribed angles, as well as the definition of a circle. We will use the following formula to find the measure of an inscribed angle: $$m\angle = \frac{1}{2}m\arc$$ where $m\angle$ is the measure of the inscribed angle and $m\arc$ is the measure of the intercepted arc. This theorem has numerous applications in geometry and trigonometry.

A worked example: Find the measure of the inscribed angle $ABC$ in the circle below, given that the measure of arc $AB$ is $120^\circ$.

$$\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw (0,0) circle (2cm);
\draw (0,0) node {$O$};
\draw (1.5,0) node {$A$};
\draw (1.5,1.5) node {$B$};
\draw (0,1.5) node {$C$};
\draw (0,0) -- (1.5,0);
\draw (0,0) -- (1.5,1.5);
\draw (1.5,0) -- (1.5,1.5);
\end{tikzpicture}$$

Solution: Using the Inscribed Angle Theorem, we have $m\angle ABC = \frac{1}{2}m\arc AB = \frac{1}{2}(120^\circ) = 60^\circ$.
